entry.title: Make Wallpaper Search use index instead of the label for expansion
entry.content:
Before, the expandedCategories_ object was using the category's label

as the key to determine if the category was expanded or not. The issue

is that for labels with periods, Polymer interprets the periods as

getting an object's subproperties (eg. 'categories_.U.S.' becomes

'categories_['U']['S']'. Using index is better in every way anyway as

the categories don't change in the lifetime of the UI.

entry.title: FSA: Return LockHandle after eviction
entry.content:
This is the final changes needed to implement BFCache logic for the File

System Access API. This change makes it so that when we attempt to take

a Lock on file with an existing contentious Lock, we can evict the Lock

if it is held by only inactive pages, and return the new Lock after

eviction.



When we evict a Lock to take a new Lock, the new Lock is pending until

the evicting Lock has been evicted. The pending Lock is not given to the

TakeLock caller until it is no longer pending.



While it is pending though, it is still considered an active Lock, and

all further calls to TakeLock will assume it exists.



If we attempt to take a Lock that is a child of a pending Lock, then it

will also be pending and the caller will not receive the Lock until the

ancestor pending Lock's evicting Lock has been evicted.



If we attempt to take a Lock that is in contention with a pending Lock,

then we can also evict the pending Lock if it is held only by inactive

pages. The callers for the evicting pending Lock will never receive it.

And the new pending Lock waits for the eviction of the original evicting

Lock that the evicting pending Lock was waiting on.



If we evict a Lock that has multiple pending Lock children, then the new

Lock must wait for the eviction of all the child pending Locks' evicting

locks.



Bug: 1382215, 1241174

entry.title: Update Paint 2D context to use the same recorder as other 2D contexts
entry.content:
The BaseRenderingContext2D class is being updated to support layers

with split recordings to separate draw calls done in layers and outside.

This will be needed to allow flushing draw calls done up until the first

begin layer while preserving the content of unclosed layers until they

are later closed.



This split rendering logic will be added to the

MemoryManagedPaintRecorder class, which is used by

CanvasRenderingContext2D and OffscreenCanvasRenderingContext2D, via

CanvasResourceProvider. Because layers are implemented in

BaseRenderingContext2D, all child classes has to use the same recorder

or else layers won't work everywhere.

entry.title: [User Education] Use accent color for help bubbles.
entry.content:
System accent color is already used for help bubbles in default Chrome

theme (light and dark) but reverts to GoogleBlue600 (GM2) when a theme

is installed.



This was not the intended behavior. The intended behavior was for the

help bubbles to match prominent material buttons throughout the rest of

the Chrome UI.



This change brings the help bubbles into line even for Chrome instances

where a theme is installed.



Note that this may produce some color clash, especially on strongly-

colored themes that do not match the system theme (e.g. dark green

theme in OS light mode with purple accent color). However, this is as

designed; the user can always change their theme or OS light/dark and

accent color settings, and the bubbles will always remain legible.

(Also note that this is an issue for all prominent material components

and highlights.)

entry.title: [iOS] Autofill Across iframes: Pipe features to JS layer
entry.content:
This CL introduces a new mechanism for checking the state of Autofill

features in the JS layer.



Booleans in TS reflect the default feature state, enforced by IfChange

in Lint. These bools are overridden by FormUtilJSFeature, which

is in turn called by AutofillAgent when initially setting up each frame,

before any form extraction or mutation tracking happens. This was

inspired by the (recently-deleted) filling delay, which was propagated

to JS by a call from the same site.



The TS lib is then available to be included by any other files that need

to check feature state.



This is used by child CLs which actually need to use feature state from

the JS layer. Unit tests in those CLs verify that the behavior of the

new code actually does change when the JS feature is enabled/disabled.

However, I wanted to split this new mechanism out so it could be

entry.title: [OBC] Cookie stores now use source scheme/port
entry.content:
This CL implements basic understanding and usage of a cookie's

source_scheme and source_port in both the CookieMonster and

in the SQLitePersistentCookieStore. Included in this work was

adding a new "unique cookie key" struct to CanonicalCookie



SQLitePersistentCookieStore changes:

The backend DB is modified to now include the source scheme/port in its

uniqueness constraint. The update and delete commands also take the

source scheme/port into account.



This means that the DB is effectively origin-bound and now depends on

the CookieMonster to manage whether origin-bound behavior is

enabled/disabled.



CanonicalCookie changes:

The concept of a StrictlyUniqueKey was added which always includes

the source_scheme and source_port of the cookie.

The UniqueKey was extended with two optional fields for the

source_scheme and source_port.



When both the scheme binding and port binding features are enabled

UniqueKey is equivalent to StrictlyUniqueKey.



CookieMonster changes:

None, the modification to CanonicalCookie::UniqueKey "just works" with

how the CookieMonster processes cookies to/from the backend store.

* When cookies are being loaded the first time and the feature(s) were

enabled and then disabled, any "extra" cookies, which differ only by

scheme/port, will be caught and deleted by StoreLoadedCookies()

(more specifically, TrimDuplicateCookiesForKey()).

* When adding new cookies, MaybeDeleteEquivalentCookieAndUpdateStatus()

will prevent "extra" cookies from being added depending on the state

entry.title: Feature DynamicScrollCullRectExpansion
entry.content:
The feature (enabled for experimental) will prevent the expanded cull

rect from getting too big when the scroller can be scrolled along both

axes. Previously a fully expanded cull rect can cover 81 times of area

for a 1000x1000 scroller that scrolls large contents. Now expand by a

half of the original outset, and give extra outset exceeding the scroll

range along one axis to another axis (i.e. the outsets along x and y

axes share the outset budget). In the 1000x1000 scroller with large

contents case, the expanded area will be 25 times of the area of the

scroll port, and the paint and compositing performance will be roughly

3 times, which can reduce janks during scroll (composited and non-

composited) when we need to repaint the scrolling contents.



A drawback could be more checkerboard tiles during composited scroll.

However, as this feature applies only to scrolling contents that are

large in both axes, which is relatively rare, the performance benefit

may compensate for the drawback. Will do a finch experiment.

entry.title: [HFM] Properly handle sites that no longer have an engagement score
entry.content:
When we moved the Site Engagement heuristic to startup, we started

processing all engaged sites at once. This works fine, but it also

ignores sites that have had HTTPS enforced, but no longer have a

site engagement score. These sites may never get their HTTPS

enforcement revoked if the user doesn't use Chrome for a long time and

the site drops off of the site engagement list.



This CL fixes this issue by getting the list of all hostnames on which

we previously enforced HTTPS. We now process these hostnames in addition

to the hostnames in the site engagement list and revoke HTTPS

enforcement when appropriate.

entry.title: get wallpaper search history
entry.content:
This is built similarly to how we treat search results.

* |WallpaperSearchBackgroundManager| is in charge of pulling the history

from prefs and translating all the strings to |base::Token|.

* |WallpaperSearchHandler| reads each history file based on the token,

decodes it, resizes it, and passes the resized file data to the UI

along with the token.

Note: We could potentially have not bothered with decoding and

resizing in the browser process, served the file within

chrome-untrusted:// in an iframe, and have the renderer resize the

image. However, I personally thought the cost of new iframes wasn't

worth it.

* Bidirectional communication between the client and handler was added

so that history could update across tabs, much like we do with theme.

* The UI code is mostly to show the connection between the renderer side

and the browser process side. No styling.

entry.content:

operating system appends periods to the end of the string in addition to

prepending "Google Chrome is trying to" before the string. The

prepending was handled correctly, but due to the fact that there was a

period already in the string, we ended up having two periods.



Here is an example of a prompt with two periods:

This CL removes the periods at the end for MacOS, and also moves all of

the strings into the common components/autofill_payments_strings.grdp

file. This is okay because we do not need to differentiate between

Chromium and Google Chrome for these strings on MacOS, that is

automatically handled.



This CL also updates the iOS string to say "Chrome" instead of "Google
